				\begin{document}$${\int }_{E1}^{E2}{\sigma }_{1}$$\end{document}(E) dE. The W is termed as the spectral weight transfer and is proportional to the effective number of electrons participating in the optical transitions within the energy range [E1, E2]. Considering the experimental energy range from 0.6 to 6.5 eV of our observed spectra, we divide the SWT into three different ranges, viz., W1 for energy range 0.6–3.1 eV, W2 for 3.1–4.0 eV, and W3 for 4.0–6.5 eV. Estimated W1, W2, and W3 and their sum W for each of the a-Si: H are shown in Fig. 6.Figure 6
(a) Optical conductivity (σ1) spectra, and (b) spectral weight of R-0, R-16, R-36 and c-Si. Inset: The estimated spectral weight transfer over three energy ranges: 0.6–3.1 eV (W1), 3.1–4.0 eV (W2), and 4.0–6.5 eV (W3), while W is defined as W1 + W2 + W3.
